article.headline: Loyola, Md. 77, Manhattan 54
article.story: BALTIMORE (AP) -- Gerald Brown had 22 points, and Loyola, Md. took control early and cruised to a 77-54 victory over Manhattan on Sunday. Loyola (5-5, 1-1 Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference) never trailed, scoring the first 15 points and 30 of the first 35. Manhattan (5-4, 1-1) shot 25 percent from the field in the opening half, and just 29.6 percent for the game. Loyola got 15 points from Marquis Sullivan, and Brett Harvey had a career-high 11 assists and 10 rebounds. The Greyhounds shot 51.7 percent from the field in snapping a three-game losing streak. Nick Walsh scored 9 points and Brian Adams added 8 points and seven rebounds for the Jaspers. Brian Rudolph's 3-pointer gave the Greyhounds their largest lead, 57-28 with 12:08 remaining. Manhattan cut the lead to 25 at 68-44 with 4:46 left on a basket by Rashad Green, but got no closer until the closing seconds.
